      "url": "https://aicompetence.org/tax-ai-not-workers-funding-ubi-in-agi-economy/",
      "title": "Tax AI, Not Workers: Funding UBI In The AGI Economy",
      "content": "Rethinking UBI When Machines Do the Work\nImagine a world where human labor isn’t the backbone of the economy. Sound far-fetched? Not anymore. With the rise of Artificial General Intelligence (AGI), that future could arrive sooner than expected. According to a 2023 report by OpenAI, up to 80% of U.S. workers could see at least 10% of their tasks affected by AI, and for nearly 1 in 5 workers, more than half of their work could be replaced [Source: OpenAI, 2023].\nNow picture this: universal basic income (UBI), once considered a radical idea, becomes the only way to ensure widespread economic participation. But how do we pay for it when traditional labor taxes start drying up?\nUBI isn’t cheap. In high-income nations, it might cost 20–30% of GDP, and in lower-income economies, it could spike to over 50% [Source: Ortiz et al., 2018; cited in Kohler, 2024].\nPull Quote: “As AGI replaces labor, we must tax what creates value—not what’s vanishing.”\nSo, here’s the real question: Should we start taxing intelligence itself—particularly machine intelligence—to fund the world’s income floor?\n“At current parameters, AI must reach ~5–6× today’s automation productivity for an 11%-GDP UBI… Raising public revenue share (~15%→33%) halves the threshold…”\n— Aran Nayebi, Assistant Professor at Carnegie Mellon University\nLabor Taxes Don’t Work in a Post-Labor World\nSwiss UBI: A Glimpse Into the Future\nIn 2016, Switzerland proposed a national UBI of 2,500 CHF per adult. If implemented, it would have required around 30% of GDP, most of which was to be funded through labor income taxation [Source: Kohler, 2024]. But what happens when labor vanishes? The math falls apart.\nMini-Story: Imagine 80% of the workforce is displaced. Who pays income tax if no one earns a paycheck?\nThe Machine Economy Is Booming—But Not Its Tax Base\nAcross OECD nations, nearly half of all government revenue comes from payroll and income taxes [Source: Kohler, 2024]. But as machines—not humans—generate more value, the tax base shrinks.\nKohler argues that funding UBI must be decoupled from labor entirely. In an AGI-powered economy, value flows from intelligence, not effort—so taxation must follow suit.\nCan We Learn from Robot Taxes?\nA Patchwork of Policies and Pushback\nRobot taxes have been proposed in South Korea and the EU, often targeting firms that use automation. South Korea reduced tax incentives to slow automation’s labor displacement [Source: Wikipedia, 2023]. But critics say these taxes hurt competitiveness and fail to capture the value from non-robotic AI systems.\nIn the News Ticker: “Should robots pay taxes?” isn’t just a thought experiment—it’s policy in development.\nRobot taxes also miss the point. They’re too narrow—focused on physical tools, not intelligent systems that drive digital value creation.\nAI Capital Outpaces Wages—And Needs to Be Taxed\nAran Nayebi’s 2025 research suggests that if AI becomes 3–5× more productive than human labor, a 33% tax on AI-generated profits could fund a UBI worth 11% of GDP [Source: arXiv, 2025].\nMeanwhile, economist Pascal Stiefenhofer warns that AGI risks collapsing wage income and concentrating wealth in AI-capital owners. His solution? Progressive AI capital taxation and a universal dividend to prevent economic destabilization [Source: arXiv, 2025].\n“AGI is both a worker and an owner… Left unchecked, this shift risks exacerbating inequality, eroding democratic agency, and entrenching techno‑feudalism.”\n— Pascal Stiefenhofer, from “Techno‑Feudalism and the Rise of AGI” (Mar 2025)\nToward a Smarter Model: Taxing Intelligence Itself\nRethinking Sovereign Wealth in the AI Age\nThe group First Movers AI proposes a sovereign wealth fund where AGI-generated profits are managed by citizens, not corporations [Source: First Movers AI, 2024]. It would work like Norway’s oil fund—only instead of oil, it taps into the intelligence economy.\nTop Takeaway Box:\n- Taxing labor is outdated.\n- Economic value now comes from machine intelligence.\n- UBI must follow this new value stream.\nProgressive AI Capital Taxation: A Practical Path\nNayebi’s simulations show that increasing the public’s share of AI profits from 15% to 33% significantly reduces the economic productivity required to fund UBI [Source: arXiv, 2025]. This means society could fund UBI earlier—before full AGI—without harming innovation.\nCallout Quote: “Don’t tax the robot—own part of the AI.”\nAI Dividends vs. Robot Taxes: What’s the Smarter Bet?\nThe Case Against Taxing Tools\nRobot taxes assume physical machines are the main productivity force—but disembodied AI systems like language models now drive far more economic change. Taxing tools is outdated. We must tax outcomes and value creation, not hardware.\nWhy AI Dividends May Win\nEconomists like Yanis Varoufakis advocate for a public share in AI profits, distributed as AI dividends. This keeps incentives aligned and ensures that prosperity isn’t limited to AGI developers alone.\nThis model doesn’t punish progress—it ensures shared benefit in a rapidly automating world.\n“Don’t tax the robot—own part of the AI.”\n— Inspired by Stiefenhofer’s broader argument recommending progressive AI capital taxation and universal AI dividends\nRisks of Under-Taxation: AGI’s Unequal Future\nThe Growing Capital-Labor Divide\nStiefenhofer’s 2025 work shows AGI could collapse wages and depress demand, even as productivity soars. Without reform, AI capital owners may consolidate global wealth—and entrench inequality [Source: arXiv, 2025].\nMind-Blowing Fact (Hypothetical): A small group of AI firms could dominate most of global GDP within a decade—unless public systems reclaim some share.\nWhy Delayed Reform Makes UBI Harder\nAs AGI accelerates, the political and financial power of AI-capital grows. Without early intervention, funding UBI may become politically impossible as public leverage vanishes.\nShould Intelligence Be a Public Utility?\nRethinking the Core Asset of the 21st Century\nIntelligence may soon be as vital as electricity or water. Treating it as a public utility, subject to regulation or profit sharing, could ensure inclusive access and funding for UBI.\nReader Challenge: Should intelligence be taxed like a natural resource?\nSome experts envision partially nationalizing AGI infrastructure—ensuring it supports human dignity rather than destabilizing democracy.\nFinal Takeaway: UBI Needs to Follow the Money\nLabor isn’t driving economic value anymore—intelligence is. If we fail to update our funding models, UBI will remain unaffordable. The future depends on how we tax and share AGI-driven wealth.\nKey Takeaways:\n- Labor tax revenue is unsustainable in the AGI era.\n- AI profit taxes, sovereign funds, and dividends are scalable solutions.\n- Robot taxes are outdated; taxing intelligence is future-proof.\n- Early reform is vital before wealth centralizes too far.\n- Intelligence is the new oil—we must tax it like one.\nFAQs\nCould intelligence really be treated like a public utility?\nYes, many economists now argue that AGI should be governed like power grids or internet infrastructure. It’s foundational to every modern service. Publicly-owned AGI—or heavily regulated models—could ensure that everyone benefits, not just early investors.\nWould taxing AI profits hurt small startups or only big players?\nMost proposals focus on progressive AI capital taxes—meaning small AI developers wouldn’t be heavily taxed. The burden would fall primarily on hyper-profitable AGI-scale firms. For example, a company like OpenAI or Google DeepMind producing trillion-dollar models would contribute more than a startup running a niche AI tool.\nCan UBI actually stabilize economies in an AGI world?\nYes. Economists like Pascal Stiefenhofer argue that wage collapse leads to falling consumer demand, even as AI boosts output. UBI acts as a stabilizer, ensuring people still have purchasing power. Without it, economies may face deflation or unrest—even amid record productivity.\nIsn’t AGI still speculative? Shouldn’t we wait?\nF"
